      <div class="prose-wrap" style="padding-top:0;">

        <!-- ============ 1. PRELUDE ============ -->
        <h2><span class="num">1</span>Prelude — From Cloud to Fire</h2>
        <p>A 1 M☉ star begins as a cold, diffuse protostellar cloud that collapses under gravity, settles onto the fully-convective <b>Hayashi track</b>, then contracts on the Kelvin–Helmholtz timescale for tens of millions of years. Once the core reaches $T_c\sim10^7$ K hydrogen reactions begin, and the full pp chain activates at $T_c\approx1.4\times10^7$ K — <b>Point 1</b>, the Zero Age Main Sequence.</p>

        <!-- ============ 2. MAIN SEQUENCE ============ -->
        <h2><span class="num">2</span>The Long Burn — Main Sequence</h2>
        <p>The Sun burns hydrogen almost entirely via the <b>proton-proton (pp) chain</b> (~99% of luminosity, below the ~1.2 $M_\odot$ CNO-transition mass). Its gentle temperature sensitivity keeps burning diffuse, so the core stays radiative, wrapped in a convective envelope. This efficient, large fuel reservoir makes the main sequence by far the longest phase of the star's life.</p>
        <div class="eqn-block">$$t_{MS} \cong 10^{10}\,M^{-3}\ \text{yr}$$<div class="eqn-note">Main-sequence lifetime scaling ($L\propto M^4$, fuel $\propto M$) — gives ~9–10 Gyr for 1 M☉.</div></div>

        <!-- ============ 3. POINT 2 ============ -->
        <h2><span class="num">3</span>Point 2 — A Star Divided</h2>
        <p>The main sequence ends at <b>Point 2</b> ($X_c=0.05$), transitioning seamlessly (no "hook," unlike CNO-burning stars) into shell burning. This leaves a sharp chemical split: an almost-pure-helium core ($\mu_i\approx1.33$) far "heavier" per particle than the envelope ($\mu_e\approx0.63$). Matching pressure and temperature at the boundary then forces the envelope to physically expand — the origin of the Red Giant Branch.</p>
        <div class="eqn-block">$$\mu = \frac{1}{2X + \tfrac{3}{4}Y + \tfrac{1}{2}Z}$$<div class="eqn-note">Mean molecular weight; a much higher $\mu$ in the core than the envelope drives the required expansion.</div></div>

        <!-- ============ 4. SGB / RGB ============ -->
        <h2><span class="num">4</span>Climbing to the Tip — Sub-Giant and Red Giant Branch</h2>
        <p>As the envelope expands at roughly constant luminosity, $T_{eff}$ falls (<b>Sub-Giant Branch</b>), until the star hits its Hayashi track and luminosity itself must climb — the near-vertical <b>Red Giant Branch</b>, powered by a hydrogen shell around a growing helium core. Deepening convection dredges CNO material to the surface (First Dredge-Up), and the ascent halts at a universal RGB-tip luminosity ($\log L/L_\odot\approx3.45$), a reliable standard candle.</p>
        <div class="eqn-block">$$L = 4\pi R^2 \sigma T_{eff}^4$$<div class="eqn-note">Stefan–Boltzmann law: a growing radius at near-fixed luminosity forces surface temperature down (SGB), until the star hits its Hayashi track — the cool boundary where no stable model exists further right — and luminosity itself must climb instead (RGB).</div></div>

        <!-- ============ 5. HELIUM FLASH ============ -->
        <h2><span class="num">5</span>The Helium Flash</h2>
        <p>The degenerate core's pressure doesn't depend on temperature, so when triple-alpha ignites at the RGB tip it runs away rather than self-regulating (peak $L\sim10^{11}\,L_\odot$ internally). All of that energy goes into lifting degeneracy — none escapes — so <b>the star never visibly brightens</b>. A cascade of off-centre flashes works inward until degeneracy is fully lifted and the star settles onto the stable <b>Zero Age Horizontal Branch</b>.</p>
        <div class="eqn-block">$$P \propto \rho^{5/3}$$<div class="eqn-note">Degenerate electron pressure is temperature-independent — the reason there is no negative feedback to stop the runaway.</div></div>

        <!-- ============ 6. HORIZONTAL BRANCH ============ -->
        <h2><span class="num">6</span>Second Fire — The Horizontal Branch</h2>
        <p>On the ZAHB the star runs two fires at once: a convective helium-burning core (triple-alpha, then $^{12}\text{C}+\alpha\to{}^{16}\text{O}$) and the still-active hydrogen shell above it, which usually outshines the core. Helium burning yields far less energy per unit mass than hydrogen burning, so the phase is brief — ~100 Myr, about 1% of the main-sequence lifetime — with core/shell competition producing a small loop in the HR diagram before helium exhaustion ends it.</p>

        <!-- ============ 7. AGB ============ -->
        <h2><span class="num">7</span>The Asymptotic Giant Branch — Double Fire</h2>
        <p>A new helium shell ignites around the inert CO core while the old hydrogen shell fades; the two shells then alternately reignite in <b>thermal pulses</b>. Each pulse convectively mixes fresh carbon and oxygen into the intershell region, later dredged to the surface (Third Dredge-Up) and enriched further by the slow neutron-capture <b>s-process</b>. Dust-driven <b>superwinds</b> ($\dot M\sim10^{-4}\,M_\odot\,\text{yr}^{-1}$) then strip the envelope down to almost nothing, ending the AGB.</p>

        <!-- ============ 8. PLANETARY NEBULA ============ -->
        <h2><span class="num">8</span>Casting Off the Shroud — Planetary Nebula</h2>
        <p>The exposed remnant keeps contracting at nearly constant luminosity, so by Stefan–Boltzmann its surface temperature climbs; once it passes ~30,000 K it ionizes the previously ejected envelope into a glowing <b>planetary nebula</b>. This ejected material — CNO-processed gas, carbon, oxygen, and s-process elements — carries the star's nucleosynthetic history back into the interstellar medium.</p>

        <!-- ============ 9. WHITE DWARF ============ -->
        <h2><span class="num">9</span>The Ember — Carbon-Oxygen White Dwarf</h2>
        <p>What's left is a naked, degenerate carbon-oxygen core (~0.55–0.6 $M_\odot$), held up purely by temperature-independent electron degeneracy pressure — more massive white dwarfs are actually smaller ($R\propto M^{-1/3}$), comfortably below the $1.44\,M_\odot$ Chandrasekhar limit here. With radius fixed, Stefan–Boltzmann forces the cooling track into the straight slope-4 line in Fig. 1 as leftover thermal energy slowly radiates away — the fate awaiting the Sun, and ~95% of all stars in the Galaxy.</p>
        <div class="eqn-block">$$L_{WD}(t) = L_0\left[1+\frac{5}{2}\frac{t}{\tau_0}\right]^{-7/5}$$<div class="eqn-note">Mestel cooling law: fast fading while young, then progressively slower.</div></div>

        <!-- ============ LIFECYCLE TIMELINE ============ -->
        <h2><span class="num">◆</span>How Long Does Each Phase Last?</h2>
        <p>The main sequence utterly dominates a solar-mass star's life. The bar below is deliberately compressed — a strictly linear scale would render every phase after the main sequence as an invisible sliver — so read the segment widths as an illustrative, non-linear ordering, and the labels for the true durations.</p>
        <figure class="fig-wide">
          <div class="fig-frame">
            <div class="timeline">
              <div class="tl-seg tl-premss" style="width:4%"><span class="tl-name">Pre-MS</span><span class="tl-dur">~40 Myr</span></div>
              <div class="tl-seg tl-ms" style="width:44%"><span class="tl-name">Main Sequence</span><span class="tl-dur">~10 Gyr</span></div>
              <div class="tl-seg tl-sgb" style="width:9%"><span class="tl-name">Sub-Giant</span><span class="tl-dur">~1 Gyr</span></div>
              <div class="tl-seg tl-rgb" style="width:9%"><span class="tl-name">RGB</span><span class="tl-dur">~10⁸–10⁹ yr</span></div>
              <div class="tl-seg tl-flash" title="He Flash — essentially instantaneous"></div>
              <div class="tl-seg tl-hb" style="width:9%"><span class="tl-name">Horiz. Branch</span><span class="tl-dur">~100 Myr</span></div>
              <div class="tl-seg tl-agb" style="width:7%"><span class="tl-name">AGB</span><span class="tl-dur">~1 Myr</span></div>
              <div class="tl-seg tl-pn" style="width:3%"><span class="tl-name">PN</span><span class="tl-dur">~10,000 yr</span></div>
              <div class="tl-seg tl-wd" style="width:14%"><span class="tl-name">WD Cooling</span><span class="tl-dur">billions of yr</span></div>
            </div>
            <div class="tl-legend">
              <span><i style="background:#2a2f4a"></i>Pre-Main-Sequence contraction</span>
              <span><i style="background:linear-gradient(90deg,var(--accent),var(--accent-deep))"></i>Main Sequence (~10 Gyr — dominates everything)</span>
              <span><i style="background:#4a3f66"></i>Sub-Giant Branch</span>
              <span><i style="background:#7a3f66"></i>Red Giant Branch</span>
              <span><i style="background:#c2492a"></i>Helium Flash (instantaneous)</span>
              <span><i style="background:#3f6b7a"></i>Horizontal Branch</span>
              <span><i style="background:#3f7a5e"></i>Asymptotic Giant Branch</span>
              <span><i style="background:#7a6a3f"></i>Planetary Nebula ejection</span>
              <span><i style="background:#4a4f66"></i>White Dwarf cooling (ongoing, open-ended)</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <figcaption><b>Fig. 2 — Relative phase durations (non-linear bar).</b> On a strict linear timescale the main sequence would occupy roughly 99.99% of the bar; here it is compressed to make every later phase legible, while the printed durations remain the true, physically accurate values discussed above.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <hr class="rule">
        <p style="color:var(--ink-dim); font-style:italic;">This is the fate awaiting our own Sun: roughly five billion more years of quiet hydrogen burning, then a few hundred million years of dramatic transformation through the giant branches, and finally an all-but-eternal cooling as an Earth-sized crystal of carbon and oxygen. The other fourteen tracks in the sidebar — from failed brown dwarfs to black-hole-forming giants — are queued for the same treatment.</p>

        <div class="credits">Content grounded in Apollo session notes: <i>Main Sequence Evolution</i> · <i>Post-MS: RGB, HB &amp; AGB</i> · <i>White Dwarfs</i> · <i>Pre-Main Sequence Evolution</i>. Built by Athena-style hand authoring outside the standard build pipeline, as a one-off prototype.</div>
      </div>
    </section>

